    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-06-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-06-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="268"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d268">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 711.6221/165</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the Swiss
                        Minister</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_RP1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ritter</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum</hi>
                </p>
                <p>The Secretary of State presents his compliments to the Minister of Switzerland,
                    in charge of German interests in the United States, and has the honor to
                    acknowledge the receipt of the Minister’s memorandum of April 26, 1917, in
                    regard to the competence of Swiss consuls, acting in the interests of absent
                    German heirs, to receive personal property in settlement of inheritances.</p>
                <p>In reply the Minister of Switzerland is informed that inasmuch as it is possible
                    that the general subject of his inquiry may be taken up in war legislation
                    before the present Congress, the Secretary of State is not at present in
                    position to give a definite expression of opinion.</p>
                <closer>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-06-01">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 1, 1917</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
